The fundamental characteristic of things as they appear to us, including ourselves and bodies, is their givenness as individual form. This is Schopenhauer’s principium individuationis and the veil of Maya. Schopenhauer, in turn, was trying to interpret Kant’s distinction between appearances and things-in-themselves and incorporate ideas from Eastern thought. ‘Behind’ appearances are the will, continually striving and becoming, without form. Here, an important distinction arises between two senses of appearance: appearance as a symbolic image in genuine art, versus appearance as mere copy, and thus as possibly deceptive. Socratic thought is the forgetting of the first possibility of occurrence,  and therefore also as the advent of a modern faith in science. This theme continues throughout his career and involves analyses of how that which merely appears is denigrated for some ‘beyond’ or ‘behind’.

Human feeling is from the ground up, a simplification of the world so that it appears as intelligible, predictable, available for human beings to use. The ultimate motive behind this is utility: without such interpretations, human beings could not survive. Moreover, different peoples interpret things according to their specific situation (e.g. climate, resources, their enemies). Thus, differences in understanding the world arise – and thus why are people so prone to tragedy and why are there so few epicureans – as the origin of distinction. The idea of benevolence is that the noble person stands for indiscriminate triumph over all opposition, and ruthlessness at the expense of self-overcoming. This benevolence is seen as a noble one, justified through a philosopher (specialization, or the concept of duty) to redeem the noble. Altruism, in a philosopher, is only seen as a moment of beauty and pure activity. Likewise, necessity is seen as the source of happiness and the formation of a new purpose. Thus, even necessity has a chance-like character to it, since that necessity is not willed. The idea is that the philosopher will the philosopher, depending upon the type of philosopher – and therefore, by no means all types), to see that which is most difficult and capable of living. is repeatedly transformed; and what is Christian about its absence of feelness.

